Here's how to implement all three:

**1 & 2 — Guard navigation with a confirmation dialog in `AppShell.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    // Only intercept back navigation from EditProductPage
    if (Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.HasUnsavedChanges
        && args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

Key points:
- **`GetDeferral()`** is required because `DisplayAlert` is async — without it, navigation completes before the dialog returns.
- **`args.Cancel()`** stops the navigation if the user chooses "Stay".
- Check `args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop` to only guard back navigation.

**3 — Custom "Cancel" back button in `EditProductPage.xaml`:**

```xml
<ContentPage ...>
    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

```csharp
// In your ViewModel or code-behind
[RelayCommand]
async Task Cancel()
{
    // This triggers a Pop navigation, which OnNavigating will intercept
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

Since `GoToAsync("..")` fires a `Pop`, the same `OnNavigating` guard catches both the custom button and the system back gesture/button — you get one consistent confirmation flow.
